Massachusetts General Laws, c. 186, \u00.proposition: Massachusetts General Laws, c. 186, § 14 provides that a landlord who directly or indirectly interferes with the quiet enjoyment of a residential tenant may be held liable, and that such interference entitles the tenant to actual damages or three months’ rent, whichever is greater, as well as reasonable attorneys’ fees.

Massachusetts General Laws, c. 218, \u00.proposition: This Court has jurisdiction over this matter pursuant to Massachusetts General Laws, c. 218, § 19.

Massachusetts General Laws, c. 223, \u00.proposition: Venue is proper in Worcester District Court under Massachusetts General Laws, c. 223, § 1, as the leased premises are located in Worcester, Massachusetts, and the alleged violations occurred in this jurisdiction.
